
Now we're entering the phase where **90% of junior developers make mistakes**.

They start coding.

We won't.

A professional developer **designs the database first**, because **the database is the heart of an ecommerce application**. If the database is poorly designed, every API, every screen, and every feature becomes harder to build and maintain.

---

# Important Change to Your Original Plan

I'm going to modify your roadmap slightly.

Instead of:

```
Architecture
↓
Backend
↓
Database
```

We'll use:

```
Architecture
↓
Business Modules
↓
Database Design
↓
API Design
↓
Backend
↓
Frontend
```

**Why?**

Because the database should support the **business**, not the other way around.

---

# Before We Design Tables

We need to answer one business question.

## What is an Ecommerce Application?

It is **not** a website.

It is a collection of **business modules**.

Think of it like a shopping mall.

Each shop has one responsibility.

---

# Business Modules

Our application consists of these modules:

```
Authentication

↓

Users

↓

Products

↓

Categories

↓

Inventory

↓

Cart

↓

Wishlist

↓

Orders

↓

Payments

↓

Shipping

↓

Reviews

↓

Coupons

↓

Notifications

↓

Admin

↓

Reports

↓

Settings
```

Each module owns its own data.

For example:

* Products own product information.
* Cart owns cart items.
* Orders own order history.
* Payments own payment records.

This separation keeps the system organized.

---

# Step 1 — Identify the Actors

Who uses the system?

| Actor    | Description              |
| -------- | ------------------------ |
| Guest    | Can browse products only |
| Customer | Can buy products         |
| Admin    | Manages the platform     |

Every feature must answer:

> **Which actor is allowed to use this?**

This is the basis for authorization later.

---

# Step 2 — Identify the Main Objects

Everything in software is an object.

Our ecommerce application has these core objects:

| Object       | Purpose                   |
| ------------ | ------------------------- |
| User         | Customer or Admin         |
| Product      | Item for sale             |
| Category     | Groups of products        |
| Cart         | Temporary shopping basket |
| Order        | Purchased items           |
| Payment      | Transaction details       |
| Address      | Delivery location         |
| Review       | Product feedback          |
| Wishlist     | Saved products            |
| Coupon       | Discount rules            |
| Notification | Messages to users         |

Notice that we're still not talking about tables. We're talking about the business.

---

# Step 3 — Draw Relationships

Here's the first business relationship diagram.

```text
User
 │
 ├─────< Cart
 │
 ├─────< Orders
 │
 ├─────< Addresses
 │
 ├─────< Reviews
 │
 └─────< Wishlist

Category
 │
 └─────< Products

Order
 │
 ├─────< Order Items
 │
 └───── Payment

Product
 │
 ├───── Reviews
 │
 └───── Inventory
```

This diagram becomes the foundation for the database schema.

---

# Step 4 — Database Naming Standards

These rules prevent confusion later.

## Table Names

Always use **plural**.

✅ `users`

❌ `user`

---

## Primary Keys

Every table uses:

```
id
```

Not:

```
userId
productId
categoryId
```

Those names are for **foreign keys**, not primary keys.

---

## Foreign Keys

Example:

```
user_id

product_id

category_id

order_id
```

Always lowercase with underscores.

---

## Timestamp Columns

Every table should include:

```
created_at

updated_at
```

Some tables also include:

```
deleted_at
```

This supports soft deletes and auditing.

---

## Boolean Columns

Name them clearly.

Good:

```
is_active

is_verified

is_admin
```

Avoid vague names like:

```
status
```

unless the column truly represents multiple states.

---

# Step 5 — Data Ownership

Each module owns its data.

| Module         | Owns                |
| -------------- | ------------------- |
| Authentication | Login, tokens       |
| Users          | Profile             |
| Products       | Product information |
| Cart           | Cart items          |
| Orders         | Purchase history    |
| Payments       | Transactions        |
| Reviews        | Ratings             |
| Wishlist       | Saved items         |

This rule prevents one module from changing another module's data directly.

---

# Step 6 — File Organization

Before writing any models, decide where everything belongs.

```text
database/

├── schema/
│   ├── users.sql
│   ├── products.sql
│   ├── categories.sql
│   ├── orders.sql
│   ├── order_items.sql
│   ├── carts.sql
│   ├── payments.sql
│   ├── reviews.sql
│   └── wishlist.sql
│
├── migrations/
│
├── seeds/
│
└── diagrams/
```

This keeps the database work organized from the beginning.

